<h1>Reproducible Research: Peer Assessment 1</h1>

<p>#####1. Read file &amp; attach it</p>

<pre><code class="r">data&lt;-read.csv(&quot;./activity.csv&quot;, colClasses=c(&quot;numeric&quot;, &quot;Date&quot;, &quot;numeric&quot;))
attach(data)
</code></pre>

<p>#####2. Make a histogram of total number of steps taken per day.</p>

<pre><code class="r">totalsteps &lt;- aggregate(steps ~ date, data, sum)
hist(totalsteps$steps,breaks=20,main=&quot;Total number of steps taken per day&quot;,xlab=&quot;Number of steps&quot;)
</code></pre>

<p><img src="data:image/png;base64," alt="plot of chunk unnamed-chunk-2"/> </p>

<p>#####3. Calculate &amp; report the mean &amp; median total number of steps taken per day.</p>

<pre><code class="r">meansteps&lt;-mean(totalsteps$steps)
mediansteps&lt;-median(totalsteps$steps)
meansteps
</code></pre>

<pre><code>## [1] 10766
</code></pre>

<pre><code class="r">mediansteps
</code></pre>

<pre><code>## [1] 10765
</code></pre>

<p>The mean total number of steps taken per day is 1.0766 &times; 10<sup>4</sup>. The median number of steps taken per day is 1.0765 &times; 10<sup>4</sup>.</p>

<p>#####4. Make a time series plot of the 5-minute interval (x-axis) and the average number of steps taken, averaged across all days (y-axis)</p>

<pre><code class="r">intervalsteps &lt;- aggregate(steps ~ interval, data, mean)
plot(intervalsteps$steps,type=&quot;l&quot;,ylab=&quot;Mean number of steps&quot;,xlab=&quot;5-minute interval&quot;,main=&quot;Mean steps taken in 5-minute intervals&quot;)
</code></pre>

<p><img src="data:image/png;base64," alt="plot of chunk unnamed-chunk-4"/> </p>

<p>#####5. Determine which 5-minute interval on average across all the days in the dataset, contains the maximum number of steps</p>

<pre><code class="r">maxsteps&lt;-max(intervalsteps$steps,na.rm=TRUE)
maxsteps
</code></pre>

<pre><code>## [1] 206.2
</code></pre>

<pre><code class="r">maxsubset&lt;-subset(intervalsteps,steps==maxsteps)
maxsubset
</code></pre>

<pre><code>##     interval steps
## 104      835 206.2
</code></pre>

<p>The maximum mean number of steps taken was in interval number 835, 206.1698 steps being the mean number of steps.</p>

<p>#####6. Calculate and report the total number of missing values in the dataset.</p>

<pre><code class="r">missingvalues&lt;-which(is.na(data))
missingcount&lt;-length(missingvalues)
missingcount
</code></pre>

<pre><code>## [1] 2304
</code></pre>

<p>The number of missing values in the dataset is 2304.</p>

<p>#####7. Create a new data set with all of the missing values replaced with the mean for that interval.</p>

<pre><code class="r">library(plyr)
get.mean &lt;- function(x) replace(x, is.na(x), mean(x, na.rm = TRUE))
new.data&lt;- plyr::ddply(data[1:3], .(interval), transform,
                          steps = get.mean(steps),
                          date = date,
                          interval = interval)
new.data &lt;- new.data[order(new.data$date,new.data$interval),]
row.names(new.data) &lt;- 1:nrow(new.data)
</code></pre>

<p>#####8. Make a histogram of the total number of steps taken each day &amp; calculate and report the mean &amp; median total number of steps taken per day.</p>

<pre><code class="r">new.totalsteps &lt;- aggregate(steps ~ date, new.data, sum)
hist(new.totalsteps$steps,breaks=20,main=&quot;Total number of steps taken per day&quot;,xlab=&quot;Number of steps&quot;)
</code></pre>

<p><img src="data:image/png;base64," alt="plot of chunk unnamed-chunk-8"/> </p>

<pre><code class="r">new.meansteps&lt;-mean(new.totalsteps$steps)
new.mediansteps&lt;-median(new.totalsteps$steps)
new.meansteps
</code></pre>

<pre><code>## [1] 10766
</code></pre>

<pre><code class="r">new.mediansteps
</code></pre>

<pre><code>## [1] 10766
</code></pre>

<p>After replacing NA values with the mean for that interval, the mean step count was 1.0766 &times; 10<sup>4</sup> (as compared to 1.0766 &times; 10<sup>4</sup>). The new median was 1.0766 &times; 10<sup>4</sup> (as compared to 1.0765 &times; 10<sup>4</sup>). This indicates that the substitution of NA values did not significantly change the mean and median calculations, which makes logical sense.</p>
